From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] drivers/ps4: Option A - skip bpcie per-function MSI domain on 6.x

Linux 6.2 reworked PCI MSI domain lookup to support per-device MSI
domains (Thomas Gleixner / Ahmed Darwish, late 2022). The legacy
`pci_msi_create_irq_domain()` + `dev_set_msi_domain()` API still
exists in 6.15 but the kernel's PCI MSI core now walks
`dev->dev.msi.data->__domains[]` for the actual lookup; the legacy
`dev->msi_domain` field is left orphaned for any device that wasn't
also installed through `msi_create_device_irq_domain()`.

Result on Baikal: bpcie_create_irq_domains() runs at probe, sets up
a per-function MSI domain for each of slots 14.0..14.7's pdevs via
the legacy API, and calls dev_set_msi_domain() — but when xhci-aeolia
later calls pci_alloc_irq_vectors(), the kernel ignores the legacy
field and falls through to the default x86 vector domain.  The xHCI
controller's MSI capability ends up programmed but the chain of
hooks we installed (bpcie_msi_init, bpcie_msi_write_msg,
bpcie_handle_edge_irq) never fires.  The MSI is delivered to the
LAPIC as APIC_SPURIOUS_VECTOR (0xef), xhci's command-completion
interrupt is lost, and every ENABLE_SLOT hits TRB_RING_TIMEOUT
(5 s) → "Error while assigning device slot ID: Command Aborted".

Diagnostic confirmed via patch 9001-DEBUG-bpcie-msi-trace boot #12:
only bpcie_assign_irqs() entry/exit logged; bpcie_msi_init,
bpcie_msi_write_msg, bpcie_handle_edge_irq were never called.

Fix (Option A from LEARNINGS.md): skip the bpcie per-function MSI
domain creation entirely on 6.x.  Children fall through to the
kernel's default PCI MSI domain, which 6.x's per-device MSI
infrastructure programs correctly for any PCI device.

Two changes:

1. bpcie_glue_init: do NOT call bpcie_create_irq_domains().  The
   per-function domains were the broken piece.

2. bpcie_assign_irqs: drop the nvec=1 clamp that depended on
   bpcie_msi_domain_info.flags.  Without our domain, that flag is
   never set anyway, so the clamp would always engage.  Let the
   kernel's default PCI MSI domain decide multi-vector eligibility.

Aeolia/Belize unaffected — apcie's MSI handling is hardware-demuxed
and runs through a different code path (apcie_assign_irqs delegates
to bpcie_assign_irqs only when bpcie_initialized).

bpcie_create_irq_domain[s], bpcie_msi_init, bpcie_msi_write_msg,
bpcie_handle_edge_irq, bpcie_msi_*_mask helpers, and
bpcie_msi_domain_info / bpcie_msi_controller / bpcie_msi_domain_ops
are left in source as dead code for now.  Removing them is a follow-
up cleanup once we're sure this fix is the right shape on hardware.

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <17146298+meerzulee@users.noreply.github.com>
---
--- a/drivers/ps4/ps4-bpcie.c
+++ b/drivers/ps4/ps4-bpcie.c
@@ -450,12 +450,12 @@
 
 	dev_info(&dev->dev, "bpcie_assign_irqs: requested nvec=%d msi_enabled=%d\n", nvec, dev->msi_enabled);
 
-#ifndef QEMU_HACK_NO_IOMMU
-	if (!(bpcie_msi_domain_info.flags & MSI_FLAG_MULTI_PCI_MSI)) {
-		nvec = 1;
-		//info.msi_hwirq |= 0xff; // Shared IRQ for all subfunctions
-	}
-#endif
+	/*
+	 * Option A: with no per-function bpcie domain, the kernel's default
+	 * PCI MSI domain handles vector allocation.  No reason to clamp
+	 * nvec to 1 anymore — let the kernel decide multi-vector eligibility
+	 * via standard PCI MSI capability + per-device domain setup.
+	 */
 	if (dev->msi_enabled)
 		ret = nvec;
 	else
@@ -527,13 +527,23 @@
 		ioread32(sc->bar4 + BPCIE_REG_CHIPID_1),
 		ioread32(sc->bar4 + BPCIE_REG_CHIPREV));
 
-	//sc->irqdomain = bpcie_create_irq_domain(sc);
-	bpcie_create_irq_domains(sc);
-	if (!sc->irqdomain) {
-		sc_err("Failed to create IRQ domain");
-		bpcie_glue_remove(sc);
-		return -EIO;
-	}
+	/*
+	 * Option A: do NOT create per-function MSI domains for child PCI
+	 * devices (slots 14.0..14.7).  Linux 6.2 reworked PCI MSI domain
+	 * lookup so that dev_set_msi_domain() no longer takes effect for
+	 * pci_alloc_irq_vectors() — our custom domain is created but never
+	 * walked.  Result: every xhci/ahci/sdhci/sky2 MSI was being
+	 * delivered as APIC_SPURIOUS_VECTOR (0xef) and xhci's command
+	 * queue hit TRB_RING_TIMEOUT.
+	 *
+	 * Solution: skip the bpcie_create_irq_domains() loop entirely on
+	 * 6.x. Children fall through to the kernel's default PCI MSI
+	 * domain, which 6.x's per-device MSI infrastructure programs
+	 * correctly.  Aeolia/Belize keep their apcie-side hardware MSI
+	 * demuxing (separate code path).  See checkpoint/docs/LEARNINGS.md
+	 * "Root cause: Linux 6.2 reworked MSI domain lookup".
+	 */
+	sc_info("bpcie: child MSI domains intentionally not created on 6.x\n");
 
 	//sc->nvec = bpcie_assign_irqs(sc->pdev, BPCIE_NUM_SUBFUNC);
 	sc->nvec = pci_alloc_irq_vectors(sc->pdev, BPCIE_SUBFUNC_ICC+1, BPCIE_NUM_SUBFUNCS, PCI_IRQ_MSI);
